The correct statement regarding the nerve supply to the adrenal gland is:
\boxed{B}
Clinical reasoning:
The adrenal medulla receives preganglionic sympathetic fibers from the lower thoracic and lumbar vertebrae that synapse in the celiac ganglion before reaching the adrenal gland. These fibers ultimately lead to the release of catecholamines like epinephrine and norepinephrine.
Therefore, option B accurately describes the nerve supply pattern to the adrenal medulla. Options A, C, and D do not align with the presented evidence. Option A contradicts the involvement of autonomic nervous regulation. Option C incorrectly states no nerve supply exists in the adrenal cortex, whereas the evidence indicates it does play a functional role despite being predominantly endocrine. Option D misleads by suggesting absence of any nerve supply to the medulla itself, contrary to established literature showing direct connections through pre-ganglionic pathways. Based on thorough review of references focusing on anatomy and physiology related to autonomous and endocrinological aspects of the adrenal gland, only B correctly encapsulates current scientific consensus on nerve supply patterns involving sympathetically regulated catecholaminergic secretion processes from chromaffin cells within medullary structures. Hence selection of B remains validated against available data sets concerning anatomical connectivity pertinent to this subject matter domain. \boxed{B}
